 ('3212', 'field', '1', 'en_us', ' understanding legal rent increases increases are limited to the cpi adjustment announced each year by the residential rent adjustment program unless the landlord can justify a higher amount the law limits these to specific reasons for a higher rent increase only one increase is allowed in a twelve month period rent can be increased if their are improvements or major repairs that add value to the property rent can be increased if there has been an increase in housing service costs such as taxes insurance utilities water garbage mantainence or managerial costs in some cases rent can be increased if there is an increase in debt service cost rent can be increased due to a previous deferred annual adjustment generally if tenants do not file a petition within 60 days of receiving a rent increase they will lose their rights to challenge the increase in most cases there is no limit on increases when a tenant moves out and a new tenant moves in once the new tenant moves in future increases are limited by the rent law read the full letter for tenants about rent increase policies understand the process of challenging a rent increase file a petition with the rent adjustment board optional attend a mediation session with your landlord to see if you can reach an agreement schedule a hearing with the rent adjustment board prepare evidence and witnesses for the hearing go to your hearing the hearing officer will decide what to do about the increase based on their interpretation of the law you and your landlord must obey the decision read the full tenants guide for detailed information '),
